y jar may not be natively supported. Tests generally should run natively by default, and dynamic class loading is allowed only when necessary. I’m pondering whether a custom class loader could read bytecodes for SecuritySupport and define the class javax.xml.parsers.SecuritySupport. However, I’m concerned about a potential SecurityException—could defining in the javax package be prohibited? It seems likely that a non-bootstrap class loader could handle defining javax.xml.parsers.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_NwzUWX5EFplSJdf10el3bebD|fc_0bb5d39a304e23be0169f8f89341d08194ae6058283c96d807", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "jshell <<'EOF'\nvar bytes = java.nio.file.Files.readAllBytes(java.nio.file.Path.of(\"/home/vjovanov/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/xerces/xmlParserAPIs/2.6.2/65acede1e5305bd2b92213d7b5761328c6f4fd9/xmlParserAPIs-2.6.2.jar\"));\nEOF", "timeout": 10}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 33554, "output": 637, "cacheRead": 6656, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 40847, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777924229105, "responseId": "resp_0bb5d39a304e23be0169f8f8861aa08194be05102b4ab8fd75"}}
